diff --git a/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/12-4-trusted-release-evidence-dry-run.md b/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/12-4-trusted-release-evidence-dry-run.md
index 86288cc..d854c7e 100644
--- a/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/12-4-trusted-release-evidence-dry-run.md
+++ b/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/12-4-trusted-release-evidence-dry-run.md
@@ -212,6 +212,58 @@ _Follow-up code review 2026-05-16 (bmad-code-review). Layers: Blind Hunter, Edge
 - [x] [Review][Dismiss] `parse_expiry` empty-string diagnostic is unreachable from `fallback_complete` (Blind Hunter LOW) — caller's `missing` check catches `""` before `parse_expiry` runs. Dead branch is harmless.
 - [x] [Review][Dismiss] Operator-controlled `expires_at` echoed into diagnostics via `sanitize()` (Edge Case Hunter LOW) — `sanitize()` HTML-escapes and length-caps to 600 chars; reducing to 64 chars is YAGNI for v1.
 
+_Code review 2026-05-17 (bmad-code-review, round 3). Layers: Blind Hunter, Edge Case Hunter, Acceptance Auditor. Reviewed commit range `d36201f..HEAD` covering CR-12-4-P14..P25, M1..M7, L1..L2 follow-up patches. 7 Story-12.4 files, +667 insertions / -136 deletions. Verifies whether the May-17 follow-up patches resolve prior items and whether they introduced new defects. Scoped diff saved to `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/12-4-review-diff-round2.patch`._
+
+- [x] [Review][Decision→Patch][Resolved 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-D6 [CRITICAL] Concurrency guard signal is hardcoded `false`; production wiring cannot ever set it `true` [`.github/workflows/release.yml:109-116`, `eng/release_evidence.py:556`] — workflow declares `RELEASE_CONCURRENT_SAME_VERSION: true` at env level, then the "Record release concurrency guard" step unconditionally overwrites it to `false` with no detection logic. The `concurrent_same_version` blocking gate is therefore dead in production. AC33 requires inspecting "run id, attempt, commit SHA, package version, tag, and previous publish state" — none of that is inspected. **Decision**: implement real detection via `gh api`. Routed to new patch CR-12-4-P58.
+- [x] [Review][Decision→Patch][Resolved 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-D7 [HIGH] `RELEASE_ATTESTATION_STATUS` hardcoded `approved-unsupported` removes any production path to `ready` classification [`.github/workflows/release.yml:30`] — every release now must travel the fallback path. Combined with CR-12-4-P26 (fallback approver chain bypass), the only way to publish is via fallback with a repo-variable approver. AC9 (attestations supported) is structurally unreachable. **Decision**: restore conditional `${{ vars.ATTESTATION_UNSUPPORTED == 'true' && 'approved-unsupported' || 'attested' }}` and add a real `actions/attest-build-provenance` step before publish that writes the attestation reference into the sealed manifest. Routed to new patch CR-12-4-P59.
+- [x] [Review][Decision→Patch][Resolved 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-D8 [MEDIUM] `RELEASE_DRY_RUN` signal is dead — workflow only triggers on `push: main`/`workflow_dispatch`, so the dry-run env always evaluates `'false'` [`.github/workflows/release.yml:32`, `.releaserc.json:12`] — fixture `local-candidate` exercises the dry-run gate, but no production workflow path can ever drive `dry_run=true`. **Decision**: add a `workflow_dispatch` boolean input `dry_run` that flows into `RELEASE_DRY_RUN`, and skip the publish phase when set. Routed to new patch CR-12-4-P60.
+- [x] [Review][Decision→Patch][Resolved 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-D9 [MEDIUM] Fallback approval is not bound to the release-definition fingerprint set at approval time (AC34/D19) [`eng/release_evidence.py:571-583`] — the fallback record carries `approver`, `expires_at`, scope, etc., but no `approved_against_fingerprints_sha256`. **Decision**: embed `approved_against_fingerprints_sha256` (a digest over the fingerprint set at approval time) in the fallback record; `fallback_complete` rejects when the current sealed-manifest baseline mismatches. Routed to new patch CR-12-4-P61.
+
+- [x] [Review][Patch][Applied 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-P26 [CRITICAL] `vars.RELEASE_APPROVER` bypass restored via fallback approver chain [`.github/workflows/release.yml:29`] — `RELEASE_ATTESTATION_FALLBACK_APPROVER: ${{ vars.RELEASE_ATTESTATION_FALLBACK_APPROVER || inputs.release_approver || vars.RELEASE_APPROVER || '' }}` chains to `vars.RELEASE_APPROVER`. Since attestation is hardcoded `approved-unsupported`, fallback approver is the de facto publish approver. A repository variable now silently authorizes fallback publishes. Fix: drop `vars.RELEASE_APPROVER` from the chain and require the fallback approver to come from a dedicated `workflow_dispatch` input or `vars.RELEASE_ATTESTATION_FALLBACK_APPROVER` only.
+- [x] [Review][Patch][Applied 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-P27 [CRITICAL] Evidence-root redaction scan will block every real release on hosted runners [`eng/release_evidence.py:424-443`] — `derive_release_checks` rglobs every file under `./release-evidence/` ≤1MB and runs `contains_dangerous_evidence`. `signing-verification.txt` from `dotnet nuget verify --all` routinely contains `C:\Users\runneradmin\...` or `/home/runner/.dotnet/...`; both match `DANGEROUS_EVIDENCE_PATTERNS`. The classifier will set `redaction_status="unsafe"` and block every healthy release. Fix: scope the rglob to a hand-curated allowlist of structured outputs (`test-results.json`, `release-readiness.json`), or run redaction only against fields explicitly marked as user-facing summaries, not raw tool output.
+- [x] [Review][Patch][Applied 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-P28 [CRITICAL] `parse_signing_verification` reports `timestamp_status="verified"` from author-signature success line [`eng/release_evidence.py:295-310`] — the regex matches `Successfully verified package 'X.Y.Z'` and assigns both `signing_status` and `timestamp_status` to `"verified"`. `dotnet nuget verify --all` does not require an RFC 3161 counter-signature; a package signed without `--timestamper` still produces the success line. CR-12-4-P24's contract was that `timestamp_status="verified"` is set only when the signing report shows a valid RFC 3161 countersignature. Fix: parse the per-package "Timestamp signing certificate" / "Timestamp:" block from the verify output and require its presence before promoting `timestamp_status`; default to `"missing"` otherwise.
+- [x] [Review][Patch][Applied 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-P29 [CRITICAL] `approval.approved` and `checks.*` string-bool truthiness bypass gates on `--evidence` path [`eng/release_evidence.py:533, 548-557, 586, 595`] — `if not approval.get("approved"):` evaluates `not "false"` as False (non-empty string is truthy), so a JSON evidence file with `approved: "false"` passes the approval gate; `bool("false")` is True at the `publish_authorized` derivation. The same problem afflicts `checks.dry_run_side_effect_attempt`, `recursive_submodule_command`, `release_definition_drift`, `post_seal_artifact_mutation`, and `concurrent_same_version` — string `"false"` evaluates truthy and incorrectly blocks; string `"true"` only blocks by accident. Fix: normalize each bool-shaped field via `parse_strict_bool` (or `parse_approval_bool` for `approved`) before truthiness tests; surface diagnostics on unrecognized values.
+- [x] [Review][Patch][Applied 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-P30 [HIGH] `manifest_diagnostics` crashes on `packages: [null, ...]` (P17 half-fix) [`eng/release_evidence.py:329-333`] — the version-set comprehension guards `isinstance(row, dict)`, but the immediately following per-row loop runs `row.get(field)` on every element regardless of type. A manifest with `"packages": [null]` raises `AttributeError`, caught by the outer `__main__` guard and surfaced as exit-2 "helper crashed" rather than the typed `manifest_diagnostics` defect channel. Fix: filter `rows = [row for row in rows if isinstance(row, dict)]` once at the top of the function.
+- [x] [Review][Patch][Applied 2026-05-17] CR-12-4-P31 [HIGH] `derive_release_checks` silently drops most manifest diagnostics from the typed checks payload [`eng/release_evidence.py:462-464`] — only `"release-definition drift"` and `"sealed artifact checksum does not match"` substrings are inspected. Missing seal, missing required fields, lockstep version drift, and attestation-state-invalid diagnostics are dropped from the returned `checks` dict. Future callers using `derive_release_checks` standalone (e.g., a diagnostic CLI) get a false-clean payload. Fix: append all non-drift/non-mutation manifest diagnostics to a `diagnostics: list[str]` returned alongside checks, and ensure `classify_release_payload` does not double-evaluate.
